segments.text: And we almost picked her back up within a month, but the weather got bad.
Where was this?
This was right south of here, about 125 miles, something like that.
4,500 feet of water.
Gee whiz.
Yeah, so the next year they went back and picked her up, brought her in, and refurbished her.
Alvin's like grandfather's ax, three new heads and four new handles, but it's still a good ax.
You know, she's...
They have a new hole in her now, a titanium hole, so she can go to 12,000 feet.
Right.
That was the next question I was going to ask you.
Her original depth was 6,000 feet, and there was some criticism about the fact this wasn't deep enough to do things like the Atlanta Church.
Yeah, right.
That's true.
Actually, we sort of... Well, people are often too conservative because...

Those spheres turned out we could have gone to 15, well, we probably could have gone to 12,000 feet in those spheres with a safety factor of one and a quarter to one and a third, because it looked like all the tests showed that they would be good to 15,000 or 16,000 feet before they collapsed.
We took them down to, one of them we were going to test and collapse in Southwest Research, and we took it down there and the tank blew up instead of,
The top blew off the tank.
So that ended that test.
We just, from then on, knew we had something that was good.
We never could quite shake loose the 6,000-foot mark.
We could have gone deeper.
We'd had to change the variable balance system, though.
That was one major change.
If we really wanted to go much deeper, we'd have had to do it.
That's the pump that pumps water in and out to keep your trim right.
And it would have worked about 7,500 feet, and that would have been the limit.
So that would have been it.
Yeah, the Neuse Hall works fine.
One of those is the sister hall has been tested to something like 22,000 feet, you see.
So we're back again being very super cautious.
And with a submarine where you're bottom limited.
I mean, if you don't go in water that's deeper than your, that's a little bit more shallow than your crush depth, you're in pretty good shape.
unless there's an atomic explosion or something like that.
In that case, it really doesn't make any sense.
That's right.
Then I think the Alvin will not be our primary concern.
It won't be our primary concern, that's right.
But it's really this 12,000 feet expansion that allows them to do the work that helps to verify deep sea spreading.
Right, and then they get into the rifts and the valleys and so on.
Now, you can't, you know, there's always a deeper place to go.
Yeah.
15,000 feet would be better than 12,000 feet.
A lot of the ocean is 15,000 feet, you know, 5,000 meters deep.
And 12,000 feet doesn't get you to a lot of the flat places in the ocean.
Of course, in some way, they're not as interesting as the places where it's wiggly.
Of course, in the valleys and the deeps, why, you have to go much deeper.
So it doesn't make much difference.
Okay.
So now, then, after your work on the Alvin, next year then, chairman of the department, right?
Yeah.
Okay.
Well, I was chairman, yeah, that's basically it.
In 62, I guess, we formed the department.
Now, so, what sort of new ideas did you try to bring into the department in 62?
Oh, actually, I didn't really try to do much at all.
Well, we got into the computer business.
We didn't have a
really big computer.
So in between 62 and 66 we got into the computer business.
We had to hire people and get the computer system set up and get a computer.
And we changed computers once from a GE-225 to a Sigma-7.
That was a, you know, that's another busy work.
It's fairly straightforward, but it takes lots of time to do things like that.
reasonably important to the department.
Right.
Well, to the whole institution.
Yeah, right.
See, this is the whole institution.
The other thing we did, we got into chipboard computers and computer systems to use on our ships, which was really started by Carl Bowen here.
He was the first person to really, well, that may not quite be true.
I think Rocky Miller was one of the first to put a computer on a ship, too.
I don't quite remember the dates.
To have a thing that was sort of a standard piece of the ship's operating gear is now the way we operate.
It's unusual for the ships to go out without one of our HP 2100s on it.
They're all operated through the department.
Do you have any prior experience in computers?
No.
So then what you're looking for is a computer man, so to speak, to bring into your department.
That's what we did, right.
That's not a problem now, of course, but that's what we were looking at.
But it should have been a problem then.
It was more of a problem.
Well, first we brought in a guy who was a computer person and not much of a manager.
He knew computers well, and he knew programming well.
But when you set up an organization like that that ends up with 25 to 30 people, the man at the top has to be also a manager.
It's more important that he knows

what you're trying to do, and how to get people to do things, and what people to use and not to use, and have somebody that knows all about the technology and everything else sort of dribbles and goes in different directions.
Yeah, it really is.
Management's an important thing, and anything that involves more than 10 or 15 people, I think, really becomes important.
So it worked well.
We have our Sigma-7, and we have, I think,
In the institution, there's at least 14 of these HPs, of which four or five belong to the shipboard computer group.
And we're continually changing it because the technology is changing.
And it seems desirable to keep in step with the technology and try to keep up with it anyhow.
It's just like these little hand computers you get these days, huh?
Incredible.
Incredible.
They really are incredible.
They really are incredible.
I might have been a scientist if I had one of those when I was young.
I couldn't pass physics.
I couldn't do the math.
So primarily the transition to the computer then that takes place, and the computer goes on the shipboard for the first time.
Were you sort of amazed at the sort of data and work the computer could do on the shipboard, or did you anticipate that?
work that a computer can do to start with.
It doesn't make much difference whether it's on a ship or not.
No, they really are amazing things.
Yes, they are.
Nowadays, it's just really nifty what people can do with them.
This changes the whole idea of what you can do with data.
You can look at it, and process it, and pull it apart, and look at frequency spectrum, and everything you want to, and just fantastic detail.
Really different.
There would, for example, have been no modeling with those computers.
That would be very difficult.
Well, people did try to model things, but they did it analytically with equations, numerical equations, and things like that.
And it just took time, lots of time.

When you get into certain integrals that you have to do numerically, that you can't get solutions for, then you have to have lots of people sitting and punching calculators and adding little things and bits together.
Wipes out the problem, right?
Weather modeling or oceanographic modeling, any of this stuff is based upon the computers.
Of course, the good ideas are hard to come by.
The original solid ideas of what to do are probably the most important thing.
And not many people have those great ideas.
And then it takes a long time to really prove them or disprove them.
I think in any field this is true.
So were there any particular problems as chairman of the department?
No, standard people problems.
You have all those all different kinds.
No, we didn't have any terrible problems that I know of.
At least if they did, they kept them quiet.
And then after chairmanship of the department?
So you were 62 to what, 67?
In the applied oceanography, to 66.
Then I was chairman of the geology and geophysics team, 66 through 69.
And of course, I'd been associated with that group before I went into the submarine business.
And I had stayed associated with them a reasonable amount during that time.
So it wasn't any big shock to come back to that group.
OK. Now that anticipates the next question.
Has the group changed or anything that you were
Any sort of surprises that came to you by the time you returned back to your original work?
No, I don't think so.
No.
We were just doing a lot more.
We'd grown.
Don't forget, this is during the period I've been here has been the big growth rate of oceanography.
And everything got bigger and better.
And we went through the big ships.
We got our first big ship chain in 58 or 9, I think it was.
59, I guess it was.
And before that, sort of the biggest ship we'd use had been the Yamacraw we had from the Coast Guard for a year and a half, for two years.
And we were doing our acoustic work from it, some cruises into the Mediterranean and back.
And that was a big change for the institution, because we started, before they'd run, well, the Atlantis was the largest ship they had, and it was quite small compared to the
Just not enough room or not enough electrical power to do all the things we do today.
That was interesting.
Then we got chain.
Then we got Atlantis II.
And then eventually NOR came along.
And so the whole picture grew about the seagoing capability of the institution.
When I first came here, we had Crawford.
which is a 125-foot Coast Guard cutter, the Bear, which is about a 70, 80-foot sort of tuggish boat, and the Alanis.
And then we used the Amicron.
That was the fleet then, but now you see we're operating, well, we're connected with Sea Probe now, and we're connected with NOR, Alanis II, and Oceanis.
plus salvin and lulut.
So our green thing has really grown.
It's enormous.
It's a big business.
But no major problems.
Well, seafloor spreading, the idea of seafloor spreading was starting.
And people were getting interested in that.
And the definition of the ridges, you know, the hazing that worked out of the structure of the bottom of the earth.
We began to see this structure.
the ties together with the seafloor spreading, the tectonic motion.
It all made an interesting picture.
And so, and then you remained as chairman of the department until?
69, and then?
Then I went to Italy for two years as deputy director of the Sackland Center over there.
Okay.
Tell me about that.
Oh, that was neat.
Well, it's a NATO organization of, they have a total of about 200 people.
And they're called ASW Center, and their work is to look at problems in finding submarines for the NATO countries.
And people are there from 13 different countries, I believe.
They have a staff of 50 scientist posts.
And usually nine of these are from the United States, and the rest are from other NATO countries.
It's located in La Spezia, which is up in the northwest coast of Italy, just beginning the lovely Cote d'Azur.
It's a very lovely place to live.
And the little town where we lived was Lerici, and that was nice.
a different world.
You're in a different environment.
It's very interesting.
The work is good.
They do quite good work over there.
All the people are picked out very carefully that go there.
It's just a heck of an interesting place to be.
How were you chosen as deputy director?
What was your conduct?
Well, just from the work I'd done with ONR.
You know, I knew a lot of people in the office.
All the people that go there from the U.S. go through the Office of Naval Research.
And of course,
We'd been doing business with Office of Naval Research ever since I came to Woods Hole.
So I knew a lot of the people down there.
And they were looking for a deputy director.
And he had to have worked in acoustics and know something about management and things like that.
And so I sort of fit the bill.
And they asked me if I'd like to go.
And I said, sure.
Yeah, you bet, huh?
Right.
So it was very nice.
And it was a terminal two-year appointment, like most of those .
Well, typically it's supposed to be three years.
But I decided that two years is enough.
And the institution has a policy which the two years of leave of absence is sort of a limit.
I could have probably gotten it for three years.
But it seemed like two years was long enough to go away.
You have a house and things like that back here.
It's a long time.
It seemed short then, too, actually, the way time goes.
I think it's interesting to do something like that, because it's different than taking a visit.
You go to a foreign country and you visit there for a while.
You don't really learn the people, learn the language, and get a feel for what the people are like.
That makes it very different, I think.
And we don't regret that at all.
When you returned back then to Woods Hole.
Yeah, right.
And then what did you begin to do?
Then I became department chairman of ocean engineering.
Because right at that time, Scott Dobbin was leaving.
So this thing was open.
I'd essentially done it before, so that's what happened.
Started out working on, well, we got involved with some things for the Navy, another acoustics problem.
I had started before I left, but Scott carried on, and then I took back over again.
And that involved doing some work for the Navy, mostly classified work.
The acoustic group at that time was in the geology and geophysics department, the way it was when I left.
So it moved over into applied oceanography.
So it's into ocean engineering.
So it's an ocean engineering now.
We just carried on, continued to do more of the same.
It's different all the time, but in one way it's the same.
So it's really fun.
Now, I have some questions I want to ask you about funding now, the next series of questions.
The nature of funding in oceanography has changed.
It seems to be it's becoming more and more towards applied oceanography and ocean engineering.
It seems like funds are more available there than they are for, I hate to use the term, basic research in science.
What's your feelings about that?
Does that seem accurate?
Are you opposed to it?
Support it?
Well, I don't really know that it's true in the first place.
I'm not so sure.
There's very few people who do basic research, actually.
Most people are solving puzzles of one kind or another, and they're not having really great new ideas or anything like that.
They're sort of putting giant jigsaw puzzles together.
If it's a difficult puzzle, I don't see where it makes much difference whether it's all applied or basic or what it is in that respect.
And there's been a lot more talk about doing that sort of thing.
But if you look at the money that's being spent, I think if you really do some of the sums, the basic part isn't doing badly at all in terms of funding.
Funding is not kept up with inflation.
And the number of people doing the work has increased a great deal.
So it makes the competition a lot harder.
Back in the early 60s, the number of people doing oceanography or oceanographically related things, there weren't very many places you could go do that.
And now there are a lot.
And of course, if you look at the total amount of money going into that type of work, it's appreciably more than it was then.
I'm not quite sure how it relates if you put in all the inflation factors.
Well, it's still more because there's more people doing it.
Just look at the institution.
We've grown from, what was it, 350 people when I came to something like 850 now.
And there are other places that have come up around the country that when we started were zero.
So that money is coming from somewhere, whether you talk about dollars.
If you talk about man years, why, there are many more now than there were then.
So I'm not sure what the real numbers are when you look at it that way.
People talk about it because that's the way Congress likes to hear it, I guess.
Anybody hates to spend their money and say, well, I don't really know what this is for.
You probably don't even do that.
And the ocean engineering, I think they're probably, it's very difficult.
Well, I don't know whether it is or not.
It's reasonably difficult these days to get money for equipment developments.
People don't like to buy the equipment.
Yet the equipment is what makes a lot of these experiments go.
The technology is what makes a lot of these things go.
And unless you develop it, you're not going to progress very far.
But that's a hard one to sell a lot of people.
And there is a lot of money sometimes wasted on developing technology that never does anything.
So it's a matter of picking out the right people and saying, what do you think needs to be developed?
Do it, then.
That's the way you have to do it.
And that's hard to do in any simple structure, I think.
What's your impression of the Sea Grant program?
Was it a good idea or a bad idea?
How did it affect you?
Oh, it gave me a lot of agony because I
going to be Sea Grant director here back in 70, when was it, two, as well as being department chairman when they first came.
And they said they had a bit of money, and we should build up this big proposal.
So we worked hard getting this big proposal together, and then they didn't have any money at all.
That's the only sour taste I have about Sea Grant.
And that really wasn't their fault.
No, I think it's been a good program.
I think they're doing some good things around the country for a very practical sense.
You know, they're supposed to be
somewhat similar to the land grant, developing the sea for use.
If you read, do you read many of their brochures that come out?
They're doing things that help fishermen, help people that work along the edges, things like that, which is very good.
I haven't followed it very closely, just because I haven't been personally involved in it too much.
It's sort of looking at it from the outside.
We have some people in our department that have had
Sea Grant proposals and so on.
But I haven't been involved in any of them myself, particularly the last quite a few years.
There always tends to be the reaction, well, if it isn't done at one of the big places, it's not going to be as good work as if it's done somewhere else.
That may be on the average true, but that doesn't mean it's always true.
And that's one thing you have to be careful of.
that you're getting too prejudiced about your own certain group's capabilities compared to other people's capabilities.
Because there's just an awful lot of smart people in the world.
Huh?
That's true.
There really are.
Especially we have 200 million of them now.
And if you take the top 1%, which isn't getting to be bad, well, there's 2 million people like that.
So it's sort of interesting.
which you were the happiest with or the proudest of in your career, what would you choose?
Gee, I guess, let's see, I'm not sure.
I was really happy when we found that bomb.
It was a matter of luck, partially, more than skill.
Perseverance, I guess.
That was a very happy time.
You really felt that you'd done something.
Well, that sort of justified the whole thing of having Alvin.
That said, no matter how much we'd spent on Alvin, right then it was all worth it.
So that was nice, because there was a lot of people saying, well, you can't do anything with that.
It'll never be useful.
So that was probably one of the nicest things that happened.
Since then, not much has happened.
Very exciting.
That really wasn't very exciting, but it sure was nice.
Have there been any, a second question of this kind, have there been any sorts of discoveries in oceanography which have come as a shock to you in the last 10 or 15 years, something unexpected?
Not really.
I guess if you look out this harbor and watch the water moving there and just this harbor alone, it's very complicated.
And you'd expect things like this to happen everywhere.
So when people find new currents or big eddies or things like that, in a way, you're not surprised because it's complicated.
You know what happens in the atmosphere to a reasonable extent.
It's not surprising that the same type of things happen
in the ocean column.
The geology, of course, is this nifty thing about the sea floor spreading with the magnetics flipping.
Now, that's quite a surprise.
That, I suppose, is probably really the biggest surprise.
And I would say that is probably, we're thinking about it, the fact that the Earth's field is flipped the way that it has and then recorded itself so nicely is really a major thing.
I think that's, I would say that's the biggest surprise.
The fact that the, well, Wagner wrote a book about seafloor spreading and so on.
A lot of people have looked at that and said, well, something's happening there.
So the fact that that has been more or less proven is very nice, but it didn't come as much as a surprise.
But the way it was proven is a neat thing, I think.
That's really nifty.
I don't know this.
Well, the Japanese claimed to have dredged up a few weeks ago and then threw back in.
That's a real winner.
That was the biggest surprise of all.
Why did it go back in?
Well, it smelled.
That's very simple.
If you're on the ship with it, I suppose it'd be easy to see that.
I guess that would be the biggest one.
I can't think of anything.
If you were offering advice to a student,
who was going to be a prospective oceanographer, what would you say should be where he should direct his energies presently?
I don't want to use the word glamour fields or hot topics, but which direction do you think oceanography is going to go in terms of development?
Well, it's going to go a bunch of ways.
And the one to go into is the one that you're most interested in.
Regardless of whether it looks like the best or not, because you'll probably do better in that one than if you try to pick out the one you think is going to be the most expansive.
It depends on what you're looking for, I guess.
Certainly in biology, there's an enormous field opening up.
But it's also very, very competitive.
The ocean engineering business of actually using
Getting things out of the ocean is going to be a big field, but it's hard to guess how rapidly that's going to move.
That's a tricky business.
Technology limitation?
Technology limitation.
And knowledge about what's there is another limitation.
We just haven't quite reached the position on that.
You know, the petroleum is one problem, and that's pretty well.
Well, we're not even sure how much petroleum we have, but we have good schemes of doing that.
The other things that are in there, we're not sure about.
I think it's really a matter of interest, rather than what the hot fields are going to be for people in our sort of standard.
I think the one that people agree here most of is that you want to get an undergraduate training in a hard science, or at least a rigorous undergraduate training, regardless of what it's in.
Because I think no matter what it does, if you do a good hard job, why?
You're going to be able to go on and do something else better.
If you start diverging too soon, learning too many facts without getting hard on one of them, you're not going to do as well.
There are always exceptions to anything you say.
I think most of the people at the institution feel that way.
If you're going to be a biologist, you should study biology and maybe read about the oceanography part of it, but not do it until you get into graduate school.
Same for physics or engineering, any of those.
